Nursing involves the improvement of health, prevention of sickness, and the care of the unwell, disabled and people who are about to die.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the four aims of nursing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The four aims of nursing are to:</p>
<li>Promote health </li>
<li>Prevent illness </li>
<li>Restore health </li>
<li>Facilitate coping with death and disability.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is it worth being a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The hours are long and complicated. School is not easy. So, if you are not sure if you want to become a nurse, the answer is probably no. But if you feel you want to be a nurse and you want the most fulfilling career on the planet, it is worth it.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How many hours do nurses work?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>No matter the facility's speciality, full-time employees on hospital nursing units typically work either three 12-hour shifts weekly (the days may or may not be consecutive) or in five eight-hour shifts.</p>
<p>Round-the-clock coverage means many nurses must work weekends and holidays, usually on a rotating basis.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the disadvantage of being a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Nursing is not simple and can be very physically demanding. Lengthened hours are often required and can sometimes be a compulsory part of work. Most nurses still engage in shift work, often having to work evenings, weekends, and vacations as part of their careers.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the bad things about being a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Top five cons of a nursing career are:</p>
<li>Physical demands</li>
<li>Extended hours</li>
<li>Virus exposure</li>
<li>Stress and pressure</li>
<li>Emotional burnout</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the primary goal of a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The goal of nursing is to help individuals, families, groups, and communities to reach an optimum state of well-being by restoring, maintaining, and promoting their health.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the primary function of a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A nurse gives care to patients and helps to handle physical needs, limiting illness, and managing health conditions. They observe and monitor the patient and record any relevant information to aid in treatment decision-making.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are some nursing objectives?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Some nursing objectives include:</p>
<li>Practice safe, evidence-based nursing care</li>
<li>Promote health through education, risk reduction, and disease prevention</li>
<li>Appreciate human diversity and the implications of a global health care environment</li>
<li>Acknowledge and assess the spirituality of self and others.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is being a nurse depressing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Nurses feel depression at twice the rate of the general public. Depression affects 9% of everyday citizens, but 18% of nurses experience depression.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do you have to be smart to be a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>You do not have to be smart to become a nurse. The nursing school has to be challenging because life as a nurse is challenging (but rewarding).</p><p>There is a lot you have to know and to know something takes a lot of work, study, and practice. So do not let doubts about whether you are smart enough to be a nurse stop you from becoming a nurse.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Are nurses allowed to have tattoos?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Formally, there is no known or fixed policy concerning tattoos and nursing. So, the topic continues being an unresolved issue in the nursing society. However, many nursing institutions and hospitals have differing theories on body ink. There is usually some freedom when it comes to visible tattoos.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Can nurses be forced to stay at work?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Nurses, too, are accountable for human lives, and therefore flexible working limits for them are relevant and necessary. A registered nurse can regularly work 12 hours in a row. Nurses who are ready and able could still volunteer for overtime if it is required.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the greatest challenge as a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The biggest challenges and issues nurses face today are mandatory overtime, safe staffing levels, and workplace safety. It increases the stress on nurses, decreases the quality of patient care, and increases the likelihood of medical errors.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the typical nursing shifts?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Around-the-clock, 24/7 care requires night shift and rotating shift schedules. The traditional night shift schedule for a hospital-based nurse is typically two or three consecutive 12-hour shifts from 7:00 p.m. to 7:00 a.m., followed by roughly two to five days off.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is nursing a dangerous job?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Health care workers, nurses, in particular, are facing higher than average levels of workplace violence, believe it or not. The rate of violence for those employed in healthcare settings is as much as twelve times higher than the rate for those in other professions.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why do nurses quit?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The most commonly cited reason for nurses to quit is dissatisfaction with the work environment. Nurses across all age groups and experience levels cited this as a reason they planned to leave their job within the next year.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is being a nurse scary?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Having to deal with aggressive patients, no free time and all those disgusting body fluids, it is hard to imagine anything worse. Well, to be fair, it is not for everyone.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the five smart goals in nursing?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Each goal and milestone you set should fit the five categories of the S.M.A.R.T. goal setting:</p>
<li>S - Specific</li>
<li>M - Measurable</li>
<li>A - Attainable</li>
<li>R - Realistic</li>
<li>T - Timely</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How do you write a nursing objective?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>When you create an objective nursing statement, be as specific as possible. Highlight individual skills, accomplishments, and goals that are highly relevant to the role.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why do nurses get paid so much?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>They have training and skills that are worth making enough money to earn a living. There is also a shortage of nurses (severity location dependent). It is predicted to get worse too.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why do nurses get paid so much?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>They have training and skills that are worth making enough money to earn a living. There is also a shortage of nurses (severity location dependent). It is predicted to get worse too. The pay has to be high enough to attract people into the field, apart from enough to retain skilled nurses in positions.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Do nurses have to be good at math?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Nursing in the "real world" generally requires fundamental math skills, but almost all programs require at least one college-level math class which is usually algebra. Some nursing schools may require an introductory statistics course as well, so if you know what schools you are applying to, be sure to check for this requirement.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What can you do with a nursing degree if you don't want to be a nurse?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Seven things you can do with a BSN degree besides nursing are to:</p>
<li>Become a nurse educator</li>
<li>Pursue a leadership role</li>
<li>Explore careers in Information Technology (IT)</li>
<li>Consider work-from-home nursing jobs</li>
<li>Work for an insurance company</li>
<li>Consider a career in pharmaceuticals</li>
<li>Explore your other patient care options.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the most stressful nursing jobs?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Emergency unit nurses tend to encounter the highest rates of burnout. A study issued in the Medicine, Health, and Medicine Journal entered that ED nurses feel that they have the most limited control in their job among nurses in different practices, which may also impact their high burnout rates.</p>
</div>
